## 14.20 The introspection angle

Why is composer in an introspection book?

Because the composer *is* introspection. Every widget is a live query into the form. Moving a widget is an update to the form. Reading the form is asking the canvas *what state are you in?*. The composer's whole shape is introspection with a graphical dimension added.

Traditional GUIs hide the underlying model. The composer surfaces it. The `composer/live-code` widget is literally a text pane showing the emitted form updating in real time. See the widgets move, see the code change. That is introspection over user actions.

## 14.21 A closing observation

The composer round-trip closes a loop that most GUI systems leave open. Widgets on one side, model on the other, with a translation layer that can lose information.

Motoi's composer refuses the translation layer. The widgets *are* the model in a different projection. The model *is* the widgets in a different projection. Neither is primary. Both are the same information, rendered two ways.

That is unusual. And useful. And introspectable.

