## 14.23 Deep-seed — headless composer

The composer verbs work without any UI. In a terminal environment:

```scheme
(define c (composer/canvas ...))
(composer/emit c)
;; returns the form; no UI needed

(composer/apply c new-form)
;; updates widget state in memory; no UI to update
```

This is how automated tests verify the round-trip. Create a canvas, emit, apply the emitted form back, emit again, assert both emits are equal. Round-trip verified without spinning up Curator or any renderer.

Headless composer is also how a REPL user can experiment with composer bindings before wiring them into a visual environment. Set up the widgets in Scheme, poke at them via `composer/set-widget-value`, watch the emitted form change.

## 14.24 Deep-seed — the composer as a doctrine

The composer's design doctrine (see engineering/COMPOSER-1.0.ENG.slat) has two non-negotiables:

1. The output is readable Scheme. No JSON blob, no binary format.
2. The round-trip is lossless. UI edit → Scheme; Scheme edit → UI; identity.

Both properties are what make the composer introspectable. If the output were opaque, you could not read what the widgets produced. If the round-trip were lossy, you could not trust that saving and reloading preserves your work.

By committing to both, the composer becomes a first-class introspection surface: every widget is a query, every emit is data, every apply is a mutation you can inspect.

Turn the page.

## 14.25 A closing note

If you have used PICO-8 or TIC-80 (both are cited in the composer spec as inspirations), Motoi's composer feels familiar — same pattern of thin widgets over a code model. What Motoi adds is uniform introspection over the whole surface, plus S-expression storage that macroexpands.

Wave 4 will walk this in detail. The seed introduces the shape.

Turn the page. Chapter 15 opens performance introspection.

## 14.26 One more deep-seed

Composer canvases can be inspected the same way any value is inspected.

```scheme
(type-of c)             ;; => canvas-record
(record-fields c)       ;; => (:bind :widgets :emit-cache :listeners)
(composer/widgets c)    ;; => list of widget records
```

Every widget record has its own type and fields:

```scheme
(type-of a-slider)      ;; => slider-record
(record-fields a-slider) ;; => (:label :bind :min :max :step :current :orientation)
```

The composer surface is just records with structured metadata. Chapter 3's `type-of` and `record-fields` work on canvas records exactly as they work on any other record.

That uniformity is what makes composer introspection composable with everything else in the book. It is not a separate surface; it is the same introspection reflex applied to a different kind of value.

Turn the page.

## 14.27 Deep-seed — LLM composed with composer

The composer emits a form. The LLM verbs (Chapter 13) take forms. They compose naturally:

```scheme
;; Rewrite the emitted form to be more idiomatic
(rewrite (composer/emit c) :goal 'idiomatic)

;; Critique what the composer produced
(critique (composer/emit c))

;; Explain the emitted form in prose
(explain (composer/emit c))
```

You are using the composer to build a form, then the LLM to interpret or improve it. Both surfaces are grounded in the same introspection reflex — data in, data out.

For teaching, this composition is powerful. A student builds a synth patch with the composer, then asks the LLM to explain what the patch does. The LLM reads the emitted form, describes the ADSR envelope, notes the sustain level, mentions the release time. Everything grounded in the actual form the composer produced.

## 14.28 Deep-seed — the composer is optional

Motoi's composer verbs are in the `extended` tier. They can be loaded or not. A Motoi runtime without the composer still has full introspection over its verbs, values, envs, macros, reader, errors, traces, Cortex, and registry.

The composer adds one more introspectable surface: the widget-form round-trip. It does not replace any of the earlier surfaces. It composes with them.

If your runtime does not need a visual composition surface, skip loading the composer. Nothing else in this book depends on it.

If your runtime does need it, load it and use the introspection reflex on canvases the same way you use it on everything else.

Turn the page. Chapter 15 opens performance introspection.

## 14.29 A closing exercise

If your runtime has the composer loaded, try this:

```scheme
(define c
  (composer/canvas (:bind '(test))
    (composer/slider :label \"Volume\" :bind '(test :vol) :min 0 :max 100 :step 1)))

(composer/emit c)
;; => (test :vol 50)   ;; default value

;; simulate a widget move (in a headless env)
(composer/set-widget-value c :Volume 75)

(composer/emit c)
;; => (test :vol 75)

(composer/apply c '(test :vol 30))

(composer/emit c)
;; => (test :vol 30)
```

Six calls. You have observed the round-trip. Widget move → emit change. Apply → widget change. Both directions, both introspectable.

Turn the page. Chapter 15.

## 14.30 Deep-seed — the fifteen composer verbs

For reference, the full composer verb list from the spec:

- `composer/canvas` — the container
- `composer/slider` — numeric slider
- `composer/button` — event-emitting button
- `composer/piano-roll` — pitch-time grid
- `composer/sprite-grid` — pixel editor
- `composer/tile-map` — tile-map editor
- `composer/timeline` — animation timeline
- `composer/adsr` — envelope editor
- `composer/instrument-picker` — dropdown
- `composer/fx-chain` — ordered effect chain
- `composer/text-field` — text input
- `composer/toggle` — boolean toggle
- `composer/color-picker` — color picker
- `composer/live-code` — text pane showing the emitted form
- `composer/emit` — canvas to form
- `composer/apply` — form to canvas
- `composer/save` — write to disk
- `composer/load` — read from disk

Fifteen widgets plus four verbs for the round-trip and persistence. That is the whole composer surface. Every one is introspectable via the same reflex.

Turn the page. Chapter 15 opens performance introspection.

## 14.31 A last note

The composer is the newest introspection surface in Motoi. It landed in the 1.4 release. If you are on an older runtime, some of the verbs from this chapter may not be available. Check `(help 'composer/canvas)` to see if it is loaded; if the return is nil, upgrade the runtime or skip this chapter.

The book is written assuming a current runtime. As always, the reference is authoritative for what is actually shipping.

Turn the page.

## 14.32 A closing observation

The composer is where introspection gets a visual dimension. Chapters 1-13 were all textual — verbs called at a REPL, records printed to stdout. The composer adds a second surface where introspection happens with your eyes and hands, not just your fingers.

Both surfaces are the same underlying data. That is the design commitment. The composer is not a special UI feature; it is introspection wearing a different suit.

Turn the page. Chapter 15 opens performance introspection — the measurable cost of every expression, including fuel and wall time and memory allocation. Every cost is queryable via introspection primitives.
